\n* {{small|Released: September 2, 2002 (UK)}}\n* {{small|Label: [[Universal Music Group|Spectrum]]}}\n|align=\"center\"| \u2014\n|align=\"center\"| \u2014\n|align=\"left\"|  \n|-\n| 2006\n| align=\"left\"| '''''20th Century Masters - The Millennium Collection: The Best Of Will Downing'''''\n* {{small|Released: June 6, 2006}}\n* {{small|Label: Hip-O / [[Universal Music Enterprises|UM<sup>e</sup>]]}}\n|align=\"center\"| 32\n|align=\"center\"| \u2014\n|align=\"left\"| \n|-\n| 2014\n| align=\"left\"| '''''Collection'''''\n* {{small|Released: November 24, 2014}}\n* {{small|Label: [[Concord Records|Concord]]}}\n|align=\"center\"| \u2014\n|align=\"center\"| \u2014\n|align=\"left\"| \n|-\n| colspan=5 style=font-size:8pt;| \"\u2014\" denotes a release that did not chart.\n|}\n\n===Singles===\n{| class=\"wikitable\"\n|-\n! Year\n! Song\n! style=\"width:45px;\"|<sup>[[Hot Dance Club Songs|U.S. Dance]]</sup>\n! style=\"width:45px;\"|<sup>[[Hot R&B/Hip-Hop Songs|U.S. R&B]]</sup>\n! style=\"width:45px;\"|<sup>[[UK Singles Chart|UK]]</sup>\n\n|-\n|rowspan=\"1\"| 1987\n| \"Free\" \n| align=center | \u2015\n| align=center | 48\n| align=center | 58\n\n|-\n|rowspan=\"3\"| 1988\n| \"A Love Supreme\" \n| align=center | 4\n| align=center | 77\n| align=center | 14\n|-\n| \"Sending Out an S.O.S\"\n| align=center | \u2015\n| align=center | 45\n| align=center | \u2015\n|-\n| \"In My Dreams\" \n| align=center | \u2015\n| align=center | \u2015\n| align=center | 34\n|-\n|rowspan=\"3\"| 1989\n| \"Test of Time\" \n| align=center | \u2015\n| align=center | 35\n| align=center | 67\n|-\n| \"[[Where Is the Love (Roberta Flack and Donny Hathaway song)#Mica Paris & Will Downing version|Where Is the Love]]\" \n| align=center | \u2015\n| align=center | \u2015\n| align=center | 19\n|-\n| \"Come Together as One\" \n| align=center | 40\n| align=center | 50\n| align=center | 48\n|-\n|rowspan=\"2\"| 1990\n| \"Sometimes I Cry\" \n| align=center | \u2015\n| align=center | \u2015\n| align=center | \u2015\n|-\n| \"Wishing on a Star\"\n| align=center | \u2015\n| align=center | \u2015\n| align=center | \u2015\n|-\n|rowspan=\"5\"| 1991\n| \"I Try\" \n| align=center | \u2015\n| align=center | 13\n| align=center | \u2015\n|-\n| \"[[The World Is a Ghetto (War song)|The World Is a Ghetto]]\"\n| align=center | \u2015\n| align=center | \u2015\n| align=center | 83\n|-\n| \"[[I Go Crazy (Paul Davis song)|I Go Crazy]]\" \n| align=center | \u2015\n| align=center | 37\n| align=center | \u2015\n|-\n| \"Something's Going On\"\n| align=center | \u2015\n| align=center | \u2015\n| align=center | \u2015\n|-\n| \"Don't Make Me Wait\" \n| align=center | \u2015\n| align=center | \u2015\n| align=center | \u2015\n|-\n|rowspan=\"1\"| 1993\n| \"There's No Living Without You\" \n| align=center | \u2015\n| align=center | 57\n| align=center | 67\n|-\n|rowspan=\"2\"| 1994\n| \"Love's the Place to Be\" \n| align=center | \u2015\n| align=center | \u2015\n| align=center | \u2015\n|-\n| \"Break Up to Make Up\" \n| align=center | \u2015\n| align=center | 66\n| align=center | \u2015\n|-\n|rowspan=\"2\"| 1995\n| \"Just to Be with You\" \n| align=center | \u2015\n| align=center | \u2015\n| align=center | 98\n|-\n| \"Sorry, I\"\n| align=center | \u2015\n| align=center | 45\n| align=center | \u2015\n|}\n\n==References==\n{{Reflist}}\n\n==External links==\n*[http://www.willdowning.com/ Will Downing official website]\n\n{{Authority control}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Downing, Will}}\n[[Category:1963 births]]\n[[Category:Musicians from Brooklyn]]\n[[Category:African-American singers]]\n[[Category:American baritones]]\n[[Category:American contemporary R&B singers]]\n[[Category:Smooth jazz singers]]\n[[Category:Virginia Union University alumni]]\n[[Category:Living people]]\n[[Category:Island Records artists]]\n[[Category:Verve Records artists]]\n[[Category:Mercury Records artists]]\n[[Category:Motown artists]]\n[[Category:Erasmus Hall High School alumni]]\n[[Category:Neo soul singers]]\n[[Category:Ballad musicians]]\n[[Category:Male jazz musicians]]\n", "text_old": "{{short description|American singer and songwriter|bot=PearBOT 5}}\n{{BLP sources|date=July 2018}}\n{{Infobox musical artist <!-- See Wikipedia:WikiProject Musicians -->\n| name                = Will Downing\n| image               =\n| image_size        = \n| landscape          = \n| caption             = \n| background       = solo_singer\n| birth_name       = Wilfred Downing \n| birth_date         = {{birth date and age|mf=yes|1963|11|29}}\n| birth_place        = [[Brooklyn, New York]], U.S.\n| genre               = [[Contemporary R&B|R&B]], [[soul music|soul]], [[neo soul]], [[jazz]]\n| occupation        = Singer, songwriter\n| instrument        = Vocals\n| years_active     = 1986\u2013present\n| label                = [[Peak Records|Peak]], [[Hip-O Records|Hip-O]], [[GRP Records|GRP]], [[Mercury Records|Mercury]], [[Motown Records|Motown]], [[PolyGram Records|PolyGram]], [[Island Records|Island]], Sophisticated Soul\n| associated_acts =\n| website            = {{URL|www.willdowning.com}}\n}}\n\n'''Wilfred \"Will\" Downing''' (born November 29, 1963 in [[Brooklyn]], New York) is an American singer and songwriter.<ref name=\"AMG\">{{cite web|last=Wynn |first=Ron |url=http://www.allmusic.com/artist/will-downing-mn0000960874 |title=Will Downing - Music Biography, Credits and Discography |publisher=AllMusic |date= |accessdate=2013-03-28}}</ref> He is married to singer Audrey Wheeler, who was a member of the R&B group [[Unlimited Touch]].\n\n==Biography==\nDowning enrolled in [[Erasmus Hall High School]] in Brooklyn, New York. Alumni of the school include [[record label]] executives [[Clive Davis]] (who founded [[Arista Records]]), [[Kedar Massenburg]] (who later became president of [[Motown]]), Stephanie Mills and singer [[Barbra Streisand]].<ref>[http://www.blakeradio.com/html/video_lounge/vl_will.shtml ] {{webarchive \n|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20070701154909/http://www.blakeradio.com/html/video_lounge/vl_will.shtml |date=July 1, 2007 }}</ref> Downing, who eventually recorded for Motown, graduated with Massenburg in the class of 1981. Downing then attended college at [[Virginia Union University]] in [[Richmond, Virginia]]. In the mid-1980s, he moved back to New York City, and worked on [[album]]s by [[Jennifer Holliday]], [[Kool & the Gang]], [[Gerald Albright]], [[Billy Ocean]], [[Regina Belle]], [[Rachelle Ferrell]] and [[Mica Paris]]. Later he sang with [[Arthur Baker (musician)|Arthur Baker]]'s group, Wally 'Jump' Junior.<ref name=\"AMG\"/> Downing then used Baker as a producer after he signed with [[Island Records]]. In 1988, Downing signed a [[recording contract]] with [[4th & Broadway]] Records, and his first solo album, ''Will Downing'', was released that same year. His version of the [[John Coltrane]] piece, \"[[A Love Supreme]]\",<ref name=\"AMG\"/> reached No.&nbsp;4 on the ''[[Billboard (magazine)|Billboard]]'' [[Hot Dance Club Songs]] [[record chart|chart]].<ref>{{cite web|author= |url=http://www.allmusic.com/artist/will-downing-mn0000960874/awards |title=Will Downing - Awards |publisher=AllMusic |date= |accessdate=2013-03-28}}</ref> Downing stayed with 4th & Broadway for just one album and switched to Island Records for his second release, ''Come Together As One'' (1989).<ref name=\"AMG\"/>  Switching labels to [[Mercury Records|Mercury]] for his fourth outing, 1993's ''Love's the Place to Be'', Downing scored his best-selling album to date with about 235,000 copies sold in the United States and over 300,000 copies in the [[United Kingdom|UK]].<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.enotes.com/contemporary-musicians/downing-will-biography |title=Downing, Will Study Guide & Homework Help |publisher=eNotes.com |date= |accessdate=2013-03-28}}</ref> He remained with Mercury for two more albums, ''Moods'' in 1995 and ''Invitation Only'' in 1997, both of which sold well.<ref name=\"AMG\"/> ''All the Man You Need'' received a [[Grammy Award]] nomination for Best Traditional R&B Album in 2000. The album included \"When You Need Me\", a duet single with [[Chante Moore]].<ref>Billboard - 8 Jul 2000 - Page 24 \"released first single \"When You Need Me,\" a duet with MCA's Chante Moore\"</ref> In 2002, Downing received the International Association of African-American Music Diamond Award.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.iaaam.com/IAAAMCelebrationPhotoGallery.html |title=International Association of African-American Music |publisher=Iaaam.com |date=2002-06-07 |accessdate=2013-03-28}}</ref>\n\nIn December 2006, Downing suffered from [[polymyositis]].<ref name=\"AMG\"/> Despite the debilitating aspects of the disease, he worked towards releasing a new album in 2010.<ref name=\"ABILITY\">{{cite web|url=http://abilitymagazine.com/Will_Downing.html |title=Will Downing Will Power |publisher=Abilitymagazine.com |date=2007-01-03 |accessdate=2013-03-28}}</ref> ''[[Love, Lust, & Lies: An Audio Novel]]'' was released in September that year.<ref name=\"AMG\"/> Beyond performing, Downing is a spokesperson for the [[American Stroke Association]]. On tour, he conducts the charity bowling event, Strike Against Stroke, to raise funds towards awareness and education in the African American community, which is disproportionately affected. The [[American Heart Association]] recognized Downing for his efforts, honoring him as a Celebrity Ambassador. He is also a keen photographer, and self-published the 2005 coffee table book ''Unveiled Series I''. He is a member of [[Omega Psi Phi]] fraternity. He has been married twice. He is currently married to his second wife. He has three children. His stepbrother is former [[Boyz II Men]] member and musician [[Michael McCary]].\n\n==Discography==\n===Albums===\n{|class=\"wikitable\" style=\"text-align:center;\"\n|-\n! rowspan=\"2\"| Year\n! rowspan=\"2\" style=\"width:20em;\"| Album details\n! colspan=\"5\"| Chart positions <ref name=Billboard_Biz>{{cite web|url=http://www.billboard.com/biz/search/charts?f[0]=ts_chart_artistname%