{"title_page": "Lincoln Chafee 2020 presidential campaign", "text_new": "{{short description|Presidential campaign of Lincoln Chafee}}\n{{use mdy dates|date=January 2020}}\n{{use American English|date=January 2020}}\n{{Infobox U.S. federal election campaign\n| committee    = Lincoln Chafee For President\n| logo         = File:Lincoln Chafee 2020 presidential campaign logo.webp\n| logo_alt     = \n| campaign     = [[2020 United States presidential election]] ([[2020 Libertarian Party presidential primaries|Libertarian Party primaries]])\n| candidate    = [[Lincoln Chafee]]\n| affiliation  = [[Libertarian Party (United States)|Libertarian Party]]\n| status       = \n|launched= January 8, 2020\n|suspended= April 5, 2020\n| headquarters = [[Jackson Hole, Wyoming]]\n| key_people   = Charles Peralo, Andrew Eichen, & Jacob Linker (Campaign Managers)<br />Caswell Cooke Jr. (treasurer)\n| receipts     = 62,546\n| receipts_footnote = \n| fec_date     = \n| slogan       = Lead with Truth<br/>Tell The Truth<br/>\n| themesong    = \n| chant        = \n| successor    =\n| website      = {{URL|www.LincolnChafee.com}}\n}}\n{{Template:Lincoln Chafee series}}\n\nOn January 5, 2020, former [[governor of Rhode Island]] [[Lincoln Chafee]] filed paperwork with the Federal Election Commission in order to compete in the [[2020 United States presidential election]] as a [[Libertarian Party (United States)|Libertarian]]. Chafee formally announced his candidacy on January 8, 2020. He suspended his campaign on April 5, 2020.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.seattletimes.com/nation-world/nation/lincoln-chafee-ends-libertarian-run-for-president/|title=Lincoln Chafee ends Libertarian run for president|work=[[Associated Press]]|date=April 5, 2020|accessdate=April 5, 2020}}</ref>\n\n== Background ==\n=== Political career ===\nThe son of prominent Republican Senator [[John Chafee]], Lincoln Chafee was for most of his life a Republican.<ref name=\"CNN\" /> Following his father's death, Chafee was appointed as a member of the [[United States Senate]].<ref name=\"Anderson\">{{cite news |last1=Anderson |first1=Patrick |title=Former R.I. Gov. Lincoln Chafee wants the Libertarian Party's presidential nomination. But he won't get it without a 'fierce conversation.' |url=https://www.providencejournal.com/news/20200106/former-ri-gov-lincoln-chafee-wants-libertarian-partys-presidential-nomination-but-he-wont-get-it-without-fierce-conversation |access-date=January 6, 2020 |work=The Providence Journal |date=January 6, 2020 |language=en-US}}</ref> He had previously been elected and served as mayor of [[Warwick, Rhode Island]].<ref name=\"Anderson\" /> In 2002, he was the only Republican Senator to vote against the [[Authorization for Use of Military Force Against Iraq Resolution of 2002]].<ref name=\"Four-Parties\">{{cite news |url=https://www.bostonglobe.com/metro/rhode-island/2019/06/04/make-that-four-political-parties-for-lincoln-chafee/JGGdRYjlFo65STHLq1JS7N/story.html |title=Make that four political parties for Lincoln Chafee |last1=Fitzpatrick |first1=Edward |date=June 4, 2019 |work=The Boston Globe |access-date=January 6, 2020 |language=en-US}}</ref> In 2007, he became an [[independent politician|independent]], later saying: \"The party left me....There was no room for a liberal moderate Republican in that party.\"<ref name=\"N-Kelly\">{{cite news |last1=Kelly |first1=Nora |title=Lincoln Chafee Just Dropped Out of the Presidential Race |url=https://www.theatlantic.com/politics/archive/2015/10/lincoln-chafee-just-dropped-out-of-the-presidential-race/448461/ |access-date=January 6, 2020 |work=The Atlantic |agency=National Journal |date=October 23, 2015 |language=en-US}}</ref> After his [[2010 Rhode Island gubernatorial election|2010 election as governor of Rhode Island]], he became a registered Democrat whilst serving in that office.<ref>{{cite news |title=Lincoln Chafee files to run for president as Libertarian |url=https://apnews.com/26b9c510789fddadf7085b2274bbfd1a |access-date=January 6, 2020 |work=AP News |date=January 6, 2020 |language=en}}</ref>\n\nOpting against a potentially troubled run for re-election as governor,<ref>{{cite news |last1=Rappeport |first1=Alan |title=Lincoln Chafee Takes Winding Road Into Democratic Race |url=https://www.nytimes.com/2015/06/04/us/politics/lincoln-chafee-democratic-nomination-for-president.html |access-date=January 6, 2020 |work=The New York Times |date=June 3, 2015 |location=Arlington, VA |language=en-US}}</ref> Chafee instead unsuccessfully [[Lincoln Chafee 2016 presidential campaign|campaigned for the Democratic presidential nomination in 2015]]. During his candidacy, Chafee criticized [[Hillary Clinton]] for her public support of the [[2003 invasion of Iraq]] and her use of a [[Hillary Clinton email controversy|private email server]],<ref>{{cite news |last1=Rappeport |first1=Alan |title=Lincoln Chafee Cites Challenges, but Hopes to Catch On |url=https://www.nytimes.com/politics/first-draft/2015/07/28/lincoln-chafee-cites-challenges-but-hopes-to-catch-on/ |access-date=January 6, 2020 |work=First Draft |agency=First Draft |date=July 28, 2015 |language=en}}</ref> but he became better known for his outwardly positive demeanor as well his unique support for [[Metrication in the United States|converting the country to the metric system]].<ref name=\"N-Kelly\" /> With troublingly low polling and fundraising numbers, as well as a poor performance at the [[2016 Democratic Party presidential debates and forums#Tuesday October 13, 2015 \u2013 Las Vegas, Nevada|first Democratic primary debate]],<ref>{{cite news |last1=Goldin |first1=Heather |title=Lincoln Chafee: I'm still running |url=https://www.cnn.com/2015/10/14/politics/lincoln-chafee-2016-democratic-primary/index.html |access-date=January 6, 2020 |work=CNN |date=October 14, 2015 |location=Washington |language=en-US}}</ref> Chafee withdrew from the race in October 2015.<ref name=\"N-Kelly\" />\n\n=== Libertarian politics ===\n{{quote box\n|text=\"I'm very motivated as an [[Anti-war movement|anti-war]] American, and also by the [[Deficit reduction in the United States|deficit]],\" said Chafee in an interview. \"Those are two big issues that, if the [[2020 Libertarian National Convention|Libertarian convention next summer]] thinks that someone with a long record on those issues... if I fit that, then yes, I'd be open to that.\"<ref name=\"Metric-Fun\" />\n|author=Lincoln Chafee\n|source=''[[The Daily Beast]]'' (August 22, 2019)\n|width=25%\n|align=right\n}}\n{{further|2020 Libertarian Party presidential primaries}}\nIn 2019, following his move to the state of [[Wyoming]], Lincoln Chafee registered as a member of the [[Libertarian Party (United States)|Libertarian Party]],<ref name=\"Four-Parties\" /><ref name=\"NBC-CT\" /> which he announced through an op-ed.<ref name=\"Metric-Fun\">{{cite news |last1=Brodey |first1=Sam |title=Lincoln Chafee: 'I'd Be Open' to a Libertarian White House Bid |url=https://www.thedailybeast.com/lincoln-chafee-id-be-open-to-a-libertarian-white-house-bid |access-date=January 6, 2020 |work=The Daily Beast |date=August 22, 2019 |language=en-US}}</ref><ref>{{cite news |last1=Chafee |first1=Lincoln |title=The party of peace: Why I joined the Libertarian Party |url=https://www.bostonglobe.com/metro/rhode-island/2019/07/19/the-party-peace-why-joined-libertarian-party/6syxdoJgnN04qcmJpAFwyH/story.html |access-date=January 6, 2020 |work=The Boston Globe |date=July 19, 2019 |language=en-US}}</ref> While noting this would be the fourth political registration throughout his career, Chafee declared that he always considered himself \"fiscally conservative and socially liberal\".<ref name=\"Four-Parties\" /><ref name=\"Metric-Fun\" /> His announcement prompted speculation from several Libertarian Party insiders and activists that the former governor was considering a run for the party's presidential nomination in 2020.<ref name=\"Metric-Fun\" /> While individuals such as former New York gubernatorial candidate [[Larry Sharpe (politician)|Larry Sharpe]] and national party chair [[Nicholas Sarwark]] were supportive of this prospect,<ref name=\"Metric-Fun\" /> others including the [[Rhode Island]] state chair [[Pat Ford (activist)|Pat Ford]] were more skeptical due to Chafee's historical positions on [[Gun politics in the United States|gun control issues]], among other things.<ref name=\"Anderson\" />\n\n== Campaign ==\nOn January 5, 2020, Chafee filed paperwork with the [[Federal Election Commission]] to form a candidate committee for the [[2020 United States presidential election]].<ref name=\"CNN\">{{cite news |last1=LeBlanc |first1=Paul |title=Lincoln Chafee files to run for president as a libertarian |url=https://www.cnn.com/2020/01/06/politics/lincoln-chafee-presidential-run-2020-libertarian/index.html |access-date=January 6, 2020 |work=CNN |date=January 6, 2020 |location=Washington |language=en-US}}</ref><ref name=\"NBC-CT\">{{cite news |title=Former RI Gov. Lincoln Chafee Files to Run for President as Libertarian |url=https://www.nbcconnecticut.com/news/politics/former-ri-gov-lincoln-chafee-files-to-run-for-president-as-libertarian/2206070/ |access-date=January 6, 2020 |work=NBC Connecticut |date=January 6, 2020 |language=en-US}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.huffpost.com/entry/lincoln-chafee-files-to-run-for-president-as-libertarian_n_5e130ad2e4b0b2520d24b270?ncid=fcbklnkushpmg00000013&section=politics|title=Lincoln Chafee Files To Run For President As Libertarian|website=HuffPost|date=January 6, 2020|author=Associated Press}}</ref> According to ''[[The Providence Journal]]'', he hired Libertarian consultant Christopher Thrasher as [[campaign manager]] and selected [[Westerly, Rhode Island|Westerly]] Town Council member Caswell Cooke Jr. for the position of campaign treasurer.<ref name=\"Anderson\"/>\n\nChafee formally announced his candidacy on January 8, 2020 at the [[National Press Club (United States)|National Press Club]] in [[Washington, D.C.]]<ref>{{cite news |title=Chafee formally launches presidential bid as Libertarian |url=https://turnto10.com/politics/chafee-to-formally-launch-presidential-bid-as-libertarian |access-date=January 8, 2020 |work=TurnTo10.com |publisher=Sinclair Broadcast Group |author=NBC 10 News |date=January 8, 2020 |location=Providence, RI |language=en}}</ref>  \n\nThe campaign struggled for months with low fundraising and poor engagement on social media. Chafee in early March exited Christopher Thrasher as his campaign manager and opted to divide the role into three with entrepreneur Charles Peralo, UPenn law student Andrew Eichen & George Washington law student Jacob Linker. The team showed a 1200% growth to social media, increase phone calls with large names for endorsements and raised more money in two weeks over what was reported for months. They also changed the slogan from \u201cLead with truth\u201d to \u201cThe Better Option\u201d. The campaign however despite visible improvements still struggled to gain a presence in the party citing issues with Chafee\u2019s past record on gun control support. \n\nChafee announced on his campaign [[Facebook]] page on April 5, 2020 that he was ending his campaign for the Libertarian Party nomination. He has not yet made any endorsement for president.<ref>{{cite news |title=Lincoln Chafee Ends Libertarian Run For President|url=https://boston.cbslocal.com/2020/04/05/lincoln-chafee-ends-libertarian-run-for-president/\n|access-date=April 6, 2020 |work=[[WBZ-TV]]|date=April 6, 2020 |location=Boston, Massachusetts |language=en}}</ref>\n\nChafee leaving the race was met with some displeasure from certain party members. Co-manager Jacob Linker was quoted in the Washington Post saying \u201cThe LP lost another good one\u201d claiming the party pushed Governor Chafee out. Judge Jim Gray & businessman Larry Sharpe would announce their own ticket for the LP nomination quickly after stating Chafee leaving as a large factor. Co-manager Charles Peralo was quoted on social media blaming the original campaign manager Christopher Thrasher for issues stating \u201cWe has the right candidate, the right platform and the right team. We sadly didn\u2019t have that for the whole campaign.\u201d.\n\n== References ==\n{{reflist}}\n\n== Further reading ==\n{{refbegin}}\n* {{cite news |last1=Budryk |first1=Zack |title=Lincoln Chafee files to run for president as a Libertarian |url=https://thehill.com/blogs/blog-briefing-room/news/476922-lincoln-chafee-to-run-for-president-as-a-libertarian |access-date=January 6, 2020 |work=TheHill |date=January 6, 2020 |language=en-US}}\n* {{cite news |last1=Hartley |first1=Ethan |title=Chafee discusses 2020 Libertarian presidential bid |url=http://warwickonline.com/stories/chafee-opens-up-on-libertarian-presidential-bid,145220 |access-date=January 6, 2020 |work=Warwick Beacon |date=September 11, 2019 |language=en-US}}\n* {{cite news |last1=Lim |first1=Naomi |title=Former Republican, independent, and Democrat Lincoln Chafee vies to become Libertarian candidate for president |url=https://www.washingtonexaminer.com/news/former-republican-independent-and-democrat-lincoln-chafee-vies-to-become-libertarian-candidate-for-president |access-date=January 6, 2020 |work=Washington Examiner |date=January 6, 2020 |language=en-US}}\n* {{cite news |last1=McGowan |first1=Dan |title=Lincoln Chafee is doing things that presidential candidates do |url=https://www.bostonglobe.com/metro/rhode-island/2019/11/19/lincoln-chafee-doing-things-that-presidential-candidates/g3gwL6INX5Wm5j833zTloK/story.html |access-date=January 6, 2020 |work=The Boston Globe |series=Rhode Map |date=November 19, 2019 |language=en-US}}\n* {{cite news |last1=Nesi |first1=Ted |title=Chafee may run for president again in 2020 |url=https://www.wpri.com/news/politics/chafee-may-run-for-president-again-in-2020/ |access-date=January 6, 2020 |work=WPRI.com |publisher=Nexstar Broadcasting |date=August 22, 2019 |location=Providence, RI |language=en-US}}\n* {{cite news |last1=Sullivan |first1=Adam |title=Lincoln Chafee is coming back to Iowa, with yet another party affiliation |url=https://www.thegazette.com/subject/opinion/staff-columnist/lincoln-chafee-iowa-libertarian-party-presidential-nomination-2020-20191201 |access-date=January 6, 2020 |work=The Gazette |date=December 1, 2019 |language=en-US}}\n* {{cite news |last1=Weber |first1=Peter |title=Lincoln Chafee, ex-GOP senator and Democratic governor, is running for president as a Libertarian |url=https://theweek.com/speedreads/887682/lincoln-chafee-exgop-senator-democratic-governor-running-president-libertarian |access-date=January 6, 2020 |work=The Week |date=January 6, 2020 |language=en}}\n{{refend}}\n\n== External links ==\n* {{official website|LincolnForLiberty.com}}\n\n{{2020 United States presidential election}}\n\n[[Category:2020 United States Libertarian Party presidential campaigns]]\n[[Category:Lincoln Chafee|2020 presidential campaign]]\n", "text_old": "{{short description|Presidential campaign of Lincoln Chafee}}\n{{use mdy dates|date=January 2020}}\n{{use American English|date=January 2020}}\n{{Infobox U.S. federal election campaign\n| committee    = Lincoln Chafee For President\n| logo         = File:Lincoln Chafee 2020 presidential campaign logo.webp\n| logo_alt     = \n| campaign     = [[2020 United States presidential election]] ([[2020 Libertarian Party presidential primaries|Libertarian Party primaries]])\n| candidate    = [[Lincoln Chafee]]\n| affiliation  = [[Libertarian Party (United States)|Libertarian Party]]\n| status       = \n|launched= January 8, 2020\n|suspended= April 5, 2020\n| headquarters = [[Jackson Hole, Wyoming]]\n| key_people   = Charles Peralo, Andrew Eichen, & Jacob Linker (Campaign Managers)<br />Caswell Cooke Jr. (treasurer)\n| receipts     = 62,546\n| receipts_footnote = \n| fec_date     = \n| slogan       = Lead with Truth<br/>Tell The Truth<br/>\n| themesong    = \n| chant        = \n| successor    =\n| website      = {{URL|www.LincolnChafee.com}}\n}}\n{{Template:Lincoln Chafee series}}\n\nOn January 5, 2020, former [[governor of Rhode Island]] [[Lincoln Chafee]] filed paperwork with the Federal Election Commission in order to compete in the [[2020 United States presidential election]] as a [[Libertarian Party (United States)|Libertarian]]. Chafee formally announced his candidacy on January 8, 2020. He suspended his campaign on April 5, 2020.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.seattletimes.com/nation-world/nation/lincoln-chafee-ends-libertarian-run-for-president/|title=Lincoln Chafee ends Libertarian run for president|work=[[Associated Press]]|date=April 5, 2020|accessdate=April 5, 2020}}</ref>\n\n== Background ==\n=== Political career ===\nThe son of prominent Republican Senator [[John Chafee]], Lincoln Chafee was for most of his life a Republican.<ref name=\"CNN\" /> Following his father's death, Chafee was appointed as a member of the [[United States Senate]].<ref name=\"Anderson\">{{cite news |last1=Anderson |first1=Patrick |title=Former R.I. Gov. Lincoln Chafee wants the Libertarian Party's presidential nomination. But he won't get it without a 'fierce conversation.' |url=https://www.providencejournal.com/news/20200106/former-ri-gov-lincoln-chafee-wants-libertarian-partys-presidential-nomination-but-he-wont-get-it-without-fierce-conversation |access-date=January 6, 2020 |work=The Providence Journal |date=January 6, 2020 |language=en-US}}</ref> He had previously been elected and served as mayor of [[Warwick, Rhode Island]].<ref name=\"Anderson\" /> In 2002, he was the only Republican Senator to vote against the [[Authorization for Use of Military Force Against Iraq Resolution of 2002]].<ref name=\"Four-Parties\">{{cite news |url=https://www.bostonglobe.com/metro/rhode-island/2019/06/04/make-that-four-political-parties-for-lincoln-chafee/JGGdRYjlFo65STHLq1JS7N/story.html |title=Make that four political parties for Lincoln Chafee |last1=Fitzpatrick |first1=Edward |date=June 4, 2019 |work=The Boston Globe |access-date=January 6, 2020 |language=en-US}}</ref> In 2007, he became an [[independent politician|independent]], later saying: \"The party left me....There was no room for a liberal moderate Republican in that party.\"<ref name=\"N-Kelly\">{{cite news |last1=Kelly |first1=Nora |title=Lincoln Chafee Just Dropped Out of the Presidential Race |url=https://www.theatlantic.com/politics/archive/2015/10/lincoln-chafee-just-dropped-out-of-the-presidential-race/448461/ |access-date=January 6, 2020 |work=The Atlantic |agency=National Journal |date=October 23, 2015 |language=en-US}}</ref> After his [[2010 Rhode Island gubernatorial election|2010 election as governor of Rhode Island]], he became a registered Democrat whilst serving in that office.<ref>{{cite news |title=Lincoln Chafee files to run for president as Libertarian |url=https://apnews.com/26b9c510789fddadf7085b2274bbfd1a |access-date=January 6, 2020 |work=AP News |date=January 6, 2020 |language=en}}</ref>\n\nOpting against a potentially troubled run for re-election as governor,<ref>{{cite news |last1=Rappeport |first1=Alan |title=Lincoln Chafee Takes Winding Road Into Democratic Race |url=https://www.nytimes.com/2015/06/04/us/politics/lincoln-chafee-democratic-nomination-for-president.html |access-date=January 6, 2020 |work=The New York Times |date=June 3, 2015 |location=Arlington, VA |language=en-US}}</ref> Chafee instead unsuccessfully [[Lincoln Chafee 2016 presidential campaign|campaigned for the Democratic presidential nomination in 2015]]. During his candidacy, Chafee criticized [[Hillary Clinton]] for her public support of the [[2003 invasion of Iraq]] and her use of a [[Hillary Clinton email controversy|private email server]],<ref>{{cite news |last1=Rappeport |first1=Alan |title=Lincoln Chafee Cites Challenges, but Hopes to Catch On |url=https://www.nytimes.com/politics/first-draft/2015/07/28/lincoln-chafee-cites-challenges-but-hopes-to-catch-on/ |access-date=January 6, 2020 |work=First Draft |agency=First Draft |date=July 28, 2015 |language=en}}</ref> but he became better known for his outwardly positive demeanor as well his unique support for [[Metrication in the United States|converting the country to the metric system]].<ref name=\"N-Kelly\" /> With troublingly low polling and fundraising numbers, as well as a poor performance at the [[2016 Democratic Party presidential debates and forums#Tuesday October 13, 2015 \u2013 Las Vegas, Nevada|first Democratic primary debate]],<ref>{{cite news |last1=Goldin |first1=Heather |title=Lincoln Chafee: I'm still running |url=https://www.cnn.com/2015/10/14/politics/lincoln-chafee-2016-democratic-primary/index.html |access-date=January 6, 2020 |work=CNN |date=October 14, 2015 |location=Washington |language=en-US}}</ref> Chafee withdrew from the race in October 2015.<ref name=\"N-Kelly\" />\n\n=== Libertarian politics ===\n{{quote box\n|text=\"I'm very motivated as an [[Anti-war movement|anti-war]] American, and also by the [[Deficit reduction in the United States|deficit]],\" said Chafee in an interview. \"Those are two big issues that, if the [[2020 Libertarian National Convention|Libertarian convention next summer]] thinks that someone with a long record on those issues... if I fit that, then yes, I'd be open to that.\"<ref name=\"Metric-Fun\" />\n|author=Lincoln Chafee\n|source=''[[The Daily Beast]]'' (August 22, 2019)\n|width=25%\n|align=right\n}}\n{{further|2020 Libertarian Party presidential primaries}}\nIn 2019, following his move to the state of [[Wyoming]], Lincoln Chafee registered as a member of the [[Libertarian Party (United States)|Libertarian Party]],<ref name=\"Four-Parties\" /><ref name=\"NBC-CT\" /> which he announced through an op-ed.<ref name=\"Metric-Fun\">{{cite news |last1=Brodey |first1=Sam |title=Lincoln Chafee: 'I'd Be Open' to a Libertarian White House Bid |url=https://www.thedailybeast.com/lincoln-chafee-id-be-open-to-a-libertarian-white-house-bid |access-date=January 6, 2020 |work=The Daily Beast |date=August 22, 2019 |language=en-US}}</ref><ref>{{cite news |last1=Chafee |first1=Lincoln |title=The party of peace: Why I joined the Libertarian Party |url=https://www.bostonglobe.com/metro/rhode-island/2019/07/19/the-party-peace-why-joined-libertarian-party/6syxdoJgnN04qcmJpAFwyH/story.html |access-date=January 6, 2020 |work=The Boston Globe |date=July 19, 2019 |language=en-US}}</ref> While noting this would be the fourth political registration throughout his career, Chafee declared that he always considered himself \"fiscally conservative and socially liberal\".<ref name=\"Four-Parties\" /><ref name=\"Metric-Fun\" /> His announcement prompted speculation from several Libertarian Party insiders and activists that the former governor was considering a run for the party's presidential nomination in 2020.<ref name=\"Metric-Fun\" /> While individuals such as former New York gubernatorial candidate [[Larry Sharpe (politician)|Larry Sharpe]] and national party chair [[Nicholas Sarwark]] were supportive of this prospect,<ref name=\"Metric-Fun\" /> others including the [[Rhode Island]] state chair [[Pat Ford (activist)|Pat Ford]] were more skeptical due to Chafee's historical positions on [[Gun politics in the United States|gun control issues]], among other things.<ref name=\"Anderson\" />\n\n== Campaign ==\nOn January 5, 2020, Chafee filed paperwork with the [[Federal Election Commission]] to form a candidate committee for the [[2020 United States presidential election]].<ref name=\"CNN\">{{cite news |last1=LeBlanc |first1=Paul |title=Lincoln Chafee files to run for president as a libertarian |url=https://www.cnn.com/2020/01/06/politics/lincoln-chafee-presidential-run-2020-libertarian/index.html |access-date=January 6, 2020 |work=CNN |date=January 6, 2020 |location=Washington |language=en-US}}</ref><ref name=\"NBC-CT\">{{cite news |title=Former RI Gov. Lincoln Chafee Files to Run for President as Libertarian |url=https://www.nbcconnecticut.com/news/politics/former-ri-gov-lincoln-chafee-files-to-run-for-president-as-libertarian/2206070/ |access-date=January 6, 2020 |work=NBC Connecticut |date=January 6, 2020 |language=en-US}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.huffpost.com/entry/lincoln-chafee-files-to-run-for-president-as-libertarian_n_5e130ad2e4b0b2520d24b270?ncid=fcbklnkushpmg00000013&section=politics|title=Lincoln Chafee Files To Run For President As Libertarian|website=HuffPost|date=January 6, 2020|author=Associated Press}}</ref> According to ''[[The Providence Journal]]'', he hired Libertarian consultant Christopher Thrasher as [[campaign manager]] and selected [[Westerly, Rhode Island|Westerly]] Town Council member Caswell Cooke Jr. for the position of campaign treasurer.<ref name=\"Anderson\"/>\n\nChafee formally announced his candidacy on January 8, 2020 at the [[National Press Club (United States)|National Press Club]] in [[Washington, D.C.]]<ref>{{cite news |title=Chafee formally launches presidential bid as Libertarian |url=https://turnto10.com/politics/chafee-to-formally-launch-presidential-bid-as-libertarian |access-date=January 8, 2020 |work=TurnTo10.com |publisher=Sinclair Broadcast Group |author=NBC 10 News |date=January 8, 2020 |location=Providence, RI |language=en}}</ref>  \n\nChafee announced on his campaign [[Facebook]] page on April 5, 2020 that he was ending his campaign for the Libertarian Party nomination. He has not yet made any endorsement for president.<ref>{{cite news |title=Lincoln Chafee Ends Libertarian Run For President|url=https://boston.cbslocal.com/2020/04/05/lincoln-chafee-ends-libertarian-run-for-president/\n|access-date=April 6, 2020 |work=[[WBZ-TV]]|date=April 6, 2020 |location=Boston, Massachusetts |language=en}}</ref>\n\n== References ==\n{{reflist}}\n\n== Further reading ==\n{{refbegin}}\n* {{cite news |last1=Budryk |first1=Zack |title=Lincoln Chafee files to run for president as a Libertarian |url=https://thehill.com/blogs/blog-briefing-room/news/476922-lincoln-chafee-to-run-for-president-as-a-libertarian |access-date=January 6, 2020 |work=TheHill |date=January 6, 2020 |language=en-US}}\n* {{cite news |last1=Hartley |first1=Ethan |title=Chafee discusses 2020 Libertarian presidential bid |url=http://warwickonline.com/stories/chafee-opens-up-on-libertarian-presidential-bid,145220 |access-date=January 6, 2020 |work=Warwick Beacon |date=September 11, 2019 |language=en-US}}\n* {{cite news |last1=Lim |first1=Naomi |title=Former Republican, independent, and Democrat Lincoln Chafee vies to become Libertarian candidate for president |url=https://www.washingtonexaminer.com/news/former-republican-independent-and-democrat-lincoln-chafee-vies-to-become-libertarian-candidate-for-president |access-date=January 6, 2020 |work=Washington Examiner |date=January 6, 2020 |language=en-US}}\n* {{cite news |last1=McGowan |first1=Dan |title=Lincoln Chafee is doing things that presidential candidates do |url=https://www.bostonglobe.com/metro/rhode-island/2019/11/19/lincoln-chafee-doing-things-that-presidential-candidates/g3gwL6INX5Wm5j833zTloK/story.html |access-date=January 6, 2020 |work=The Boston Globe |series=Rhode Map |date=November 19, 2019 |language=en-US}}\n* {{cite news |last1=Nesi |first1=Ted |title=Chafee may run for president again in 2020 |url=https://www.wpri.com/news/politics/chafee-may-run-for-president-again-in-2020/ |access-date=January 6, 2020 |work=WPRI.com |publisher=Nexstar Broadcasting |date=August 22, 2019 |location=Providence, RI |language=en-US}}\n* {{cite news |last1=Sullivan |first1=Adam |title=Lincoln Chafee is coming back to Iowa, with yet another party affiliation |url=https://www.thegazette.com/subject/opinion/staff-columnist/lincoln-chafee-iowa-libertarian-party-presidential-nomination-2020-20191201 |access-date=January 6, 2020 |work=The Gazette |date=December 1, 2019 |language=en-US}}\n* {{cite news |last1=Weber |first1=Peter |title=Lincoln Chafee, ex-GOP senator and Democratic governor, is running for pr